<TrustPageLayout
  title="How we make money — DubaiPoints"
  description="A plain-English explanation of how DubaiPoints is funded, how affiliate commissions work, and the firewall between commercial relationships and editorial decisions."
  eyebrow="How we make money"
  heading="What pays for DubaiPoints — and what doesn't shape what we publish."
  lastUpdated={new Date("2026-05-06")}
>
  <section>
    <h2>Today, nothing</h2>
    <p>At launch, DubaiPoints has no revenue. The site is funded out of pocket by its founder while the audience is being built. There are no affiliate links live, no sponsored content, and no display advertising on the site as of the date above.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What we plan</h2>
    <p>Over time, DubaiPoints expects to be funded by a combination of:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Affiliate commission.</strong> When a reader applies for a card or opens an account through one of our outbound links, the bank may pay us a commission. We will mark every such link with an asterisk (<span class="ast">*</span>) and disclose it inline.</li>
      <li><strong>Sponsored content.</strong> A bank, airline, or merchant may pay us to publish a clearly-badged sponsored article. Sponsored articles will carry a "Sponsored by [Partner]" attribution at the top, a distinct background tint, and will be excluded from any editorial "Best of" or "Today's Best Deals" placement unless paid placement is also explicit.</li>
      <li><strong>A reader newsletter.</strong> One sponsor mention per send, clearly demarcated.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What we will never do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Accept payment to rank a product higher.</strong> No bank, card issuer, or programme can buy a better verdict, a higher position in a list, or inclusion in a "Best of" feature.</li>
      <li><strong>Hide a commercial relationship.</strong> Every commercial outbound link is asterisked. Every sponsored article is badged. Every newsletter sponsor is named.</li>
      <li><strong>Run pop-ups, interstitials, or auto-playing ads</strong> that push content below the fold or compromise mobile readability.</li>
      <li><strong>Sell reader email addresses or browsing data.</strong> Cloudflare Web Analytics, our only third-party measurement tool, does not use cookies and does not fingerprint users.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The asterisk system</h2>
    <p>Whenever you see an asterisk (<span class="ast">*</span>) next to a link or product name, it means DubaiPoints may earn a commission if you click that link and apply for the product. The asterisk is the same on every page. You can always check the meaning here — it is the only thing the asterisk ever means on this site.</p>
    <p><strong>The commission does not change our editorial verdict.</strong> We have rated cards from banks we have an affiliate relationship with as the worst card on the page when we believed they were. We will continue to do that.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Editorial firewall</h2>
    <p>Editorial decisions — what to cover, how to rate it, where it ranks in a comparison — are made independently of any commercial relationship. The editor publishes the verdict; the commercial side fits affiliate links and sponsorships around the verdict, never the other way around. If a bank that pays us a commission asks for a change to a review's tone, ranking, or wording, we say no.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this means in practice</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>If a card is bad, we say so — even if the bank is an affiliate partner.</li>
      <li>If a sponsor wants a sponsored article, it is published as "Sponsored by [Partner]" and excluded from editorial best-of features.</li>
      <li>If we get something wrong, we update the page and note the correction. See <a href="/editorial-policy/">our editorial policy</a> for full details.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

